</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Effects_of_extreme_heat_on_the_body_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1686388512" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Effects_of_extreme_heat_on_the_body_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1686388512 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Effects_of_extreme_heat_on_the_body_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.png?v=1686388512 320w" width="1682" height="1121" alt="Effects of extreme heat on the body - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Effects of extreme heat on the body - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-36_"/><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-jHkVzv gbyaRg pf-37_"><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-38_"><b>Increased blood pressure </b>- The heat strain causes blood vessels to dilate, leading to lower blood pressure and a heavier workload for the heart.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-40_"><b>Dehydration</b> - High temperatures result in excessive sweating, leading to fluid and electrolyte loss and the risk of dehydration.
